# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bullet-graphs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] A **bar chart** or **bar graph** is a chart or graph that presents categorical data with rectangular bars with heights or lengths proportional to the values that they represent.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] The bars can be plotted vertically or horizontally.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] A vertical bar chart is sometimes called a **column chart** and has been identified as the prototype of charts.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] A bar graph shows comparisons among discrete categories.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] One axis of the chart shows the specific categories being compared, and the other axis represents a measured value.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Some bar graphs present bars clustered or stacked in groups of more than one, showing the values of more than one measured variable.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Many sources consider William Playfair (1759–1824) to have invented the bar chart and the *Exports and Imports of Scotland to and from different parts for one Year from Christmas 1780 to Christmas 1781* graph from his *The Commercial and Political Atlas* to be the first bar chart in history.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Diagrams of the velocity of a constantly accelerating object against time published in *The Latitude of Forms* (attributed to Jacobus de Sancto Martino or, perhaps, to Nicole Oresme) about 300 years before can be interpreted as "proto bar charts".
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Bar graphs/charts provide a visual presentation of categorical data.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Categorical data is a grouping of data into discrete groups, such as months of the year, age group, shoe sizes, and animals.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] These categories are usually qualitative.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] In a column (vertical) bar chart, categories appear along the horizontal axis and the height of the bar corresponds to the value of each category.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Bar charts have a discrete domain of categories, and are usually scaled so that all the data can fit on the chart.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] When there is no natural ordering of the categories being compared, bars on the chart may be arranged in any order.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Bar charts arranged from highest to lowest incidence are called Pareto charts.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] In many cases it is considered correct to use zero as the value at the end of each bar opposite to the end that indicates the data value, because using a non-zero value can make values that are relatively similar have deceptively different bar lengths.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] However, sometimes this approach is not appropriate or not feasible, such as with temperatures in Celsius or Fahrenheit where zero is a somewhat arbitrary value, and with logarithmic charts where "log(0)" would be infinitely far away.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Bar graphs can also be used for more complex comparisons of data with grouped (or "clustered") bar charts, and stacked bar charts.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] In **grouped (clustered) bar charts**, for each categorical group there are two or more bars color-coded to represent a particular grouping.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] For example, a business owner with two stores might make a grouped bar chart with different colored bars to represent each store: the horizontal axis would show the months of the year and the vertical axis would show revenue.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Alternatively, **Stacked bar charts** (also known as **Composite bar charts**) stack bars on top of each other so that the height of the resulting stack shows the combined result.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Unlike a grouped bar chart where each factor is displayed next to another, each with their own bar, the stacked bar chart displays multiple data points stacked in a single row or column.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] This may, for instance, take the form of uniform height bars charting a time series with internal stacked colours indicating the percentage participation of a sub-type of data.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Another example would be a time series displaying total numbers, with internal colors indicating participation in the total by sub-types.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts are not suited to data sets having both positive and negative values.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Grouped bar charts usually present the information in the same order in each grouping.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Stacked bar charts present the information in the same sequence on each bar.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Variable-width bar charts, sometimes abbreviated *variwide* (bar) charts, are bar charts having bars with non-uniform widths.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Roles of the vertical and horizontal axes may be reversed, depending on the desired application.
[src:bullet-graphs/bar-chart] Examples of variable-width bar charts are shown at Wikimedia Commons.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] A **bullet graph** is a variation of a bar graph developed by Stephen Few.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] Seemingly inspired by the traditional thermometer charts and progress bars found in many dashboards, the bullet graph serves as a replacement for dashboard gauges and meters.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] Bullet graphs were developed to overcome the fundamental issues of gauges and meters: they typically display too little information, require too much space, and are cluttered with useless and distracting decorations.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] The qualitative ranges are displayed as varying intensities of a single hue to make them discernible by those who are color blind and to restrict the use of colors on the dashboard to a minimum.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] Bullet graphs can be created in R (programming language) using the bulletgraph() function developed by Marco Torchiano.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] Below is an example of R code using the bulletgraph() function to create a black-and-white and colored bullet graph.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] Bullet graphs may be horizontal or vertical and may be stacked to allow comparisons of several measures at once.
[src:bullet-graphs/bullet-graph] More information about bullet graphs can be found in the book *Information Dashboard Design* by Stephen Few.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In computer information systems, a **dashboard** is a type of graphical user interface which often provides at-a-glance views of data relevant to a particular objective or process through a combination of visualizations and summary information.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In other usage, "dashboard" is another name for "progress report" or "report" and is considered a form of data visualization.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The dashboard is often accessible by a web browser and is typically linked to regularly updating data sources.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards are often interactive and facilitate users to explore the data themselves, usually by clicking into elements to view more detailed information.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The term dashboard originates from the automobile dashboard where drivers monitor the major functions at a glance via the instrument panel.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The idea of digital dashboards followed the study of decision support systems in the 1970s.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Early predecessors of the modern business dashboard were first developed in the 1980s in the form of Executive Information Systems (EISs).
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Due to problems primarily with data refreshing and handling, it was soon realized that the approach wasn't practical as information was often incomplete, unreliable, and spread across too many disparate sources.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Thus, EISs hibernated until the 1990s when the information age quickened pace and data warehousing, and online analytical processing (OLAP) allowed dashboards to function adequately.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Despite the availability of enabling technologies, the dashboard use didn't become popular until later in that decade, with the rise of key performance indicators (KPIs), and the introduction of Robert S.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In the late 1990s, Microsoft promoted a concept known as the Digital Nervous System and "digital dashboards" were described as being one leg of that concept.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Today, the use of dashboards forms an important part of Business Performance Management (BPM).
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Initially dashboards were used for monitoring purposes, now with the advancement of technology, dashboards are being used for more analytical purposes.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The use of dashboards has now been incorporating; scenario analysis, drill down capabilities, and presentation format flexibility.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Digital dashboards allow managers to monitor the contribution of the various departments in their organization.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In addition, they enable “rolling up” of information to present a consolidated view across an organization.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] To gauge exactly how well an organization is performing overall, digital dashboards allow you to capture and report specific data points from each department within the organization, thus providing a "snapshot" of performance.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards offers a holistic view of the entire business as it gives the manager a bird's eye view into the performance of sales, data inventory, web traffic, social media analytics and other associated data that is visually presented on a single dashboard.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards lead to better management of marketing/financial strategies as a dashboard for the display of marketing data makes the process of marketing easier and more reliable as compared to doing it manually.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Web analytics play a crucial role in shaping the marketing strategy of many businesses.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards also facilitate for better tracking of sales and financial reporting as the data is more precise and in one area.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Lastly, dashboards offer for better customer service through monitoring because they keep both the managers and the clients updated on the project progress through automated emails and notifications.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards can be broken down according to role and are either strategic, analytical, operational, or informational.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards are the 3rd step on the information ladder, demonstrating the conversion of data to increasingly valuable insights.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Strategic dashboards support managers at any level in an organization and provide the quick overview that decision-makers need to monitor the health and opportunities of the business.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards of this type focus on high-level measures of performance and forecasts.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Strategic dashboards benefit from static snapshots of data (daily, weekly, monthly, and quarterly) that are not constantly changing from one moment to the next.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards for analytical purposes often include more context, comparisons, and history, along with subtler performance evaluators.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In addition, analytical dashboards typically support interactions with the data, such as drilling down into the underlying details.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards for monitoring operations are often designed differently from those that support strategic decision making or data analysis and often require monitoring of activities and events that are constantly changing and might require attention and response at a moment's notice.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Digital dashboards may be laid out to track the flows inherent in the business processes that they monitor.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Graphically, users may see the high-level processes and then drill down into low-level data.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] This level of detail is often buried deep within the corporate enterprise and otherwise unavailable to the senior executives.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Three main types of digital dashboards dominate the market today: desktop software applications, web-browser-based applications, and desktop applications are also known as desktop widgets.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Both Desktop and Browser-based providers enable the distribution of dashboards via a web browser.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] An example of the latter is web-based-browser Asana, which helps teams orchestrate their work, from daily tasks to strategic cross-functional initiatives.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] With it, teams can manage everything from company objectives to digital transformation to product launches and marketing campaigns.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Specialized dashboards may track all corporate functions.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Examples include human resources, recruiting, sales, operations, security, information technology, project management, customer relationship management, digital marketing and many more departmental dashboards.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For a smaller organization like a startup a compact startup scorecard dashboard tracks important activities across lot of domains ranging from social media to sales.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Digital dashboard projects involve business units as the driver and the information technology department as the enabler.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Therefore, the success of dashboard projects depends on the relevancy/importance of information provided within the dashboard.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] This includes the metrics chosen to monitor and the timeliness of the data forming those metrics; data must be up to date and accurate.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Key performance indicators, balanced scorecards, and sales performance figures are some of the content appropriate on business dashboards.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards involve the combination of visual and functional features.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] This combination of features helps improve cognition and interpretation.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] A performance dashboard sits at the intersection of two powerful disciplines: business intelligence and performance management.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Therefore, there are different users who could use these dashboards for different reasons.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, a level of workers could look at monitoring inventory while those in more managerial roles can look at lagging measure.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Then executives could utilize the dashboard to evaluate strategic performance against objectives.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Balanced scorecards and dashboards have been linked together as if they were interchangeable.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] However, although both visually display critical information, the difference is in the format: Scorecards can open the quality of an operation while dashboards provide calculated direction.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] A balanced scorecard has what they called a "prescriptive" format.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Each of these sections ensures that a Balanced Scorecard is essentially connected to the businesses critical strategic needs.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The design of a dashboard is more loosely defined.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards are usually a series of graphics, charts, gauges and other visual indicators that can be monitored and interpreted.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Even when there is a strategic link, on a dashboard, it may not be noticed as such since objectives are not normally present on dashboards.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] However, dashboards can be customized to link their graphs and charts to strategic objectives.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Digital dashboard technology is available "out-of-the-box" from many software providers.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Some companies, however, continue to do in-house development and maintenance of dashboard applications.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, GE Aviation has developed a proprietary software/portal called "Digital Cockpit" to monitor the trends in the aircraft spare parts business.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] A good information design will clearly communicate key information to users and makes supporting information easily accessible.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] There are a few key elements to a good dashboard:.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] A research-based framework for Business Intelligence dashboard design suggests that "cross-visual interactivity" is the most impactful of all features.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards serve as a visual representation for a company to monitor progress and trends, not only among themselves but against other companies as well.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards and visualizations contain data that is updated in real time.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, if the underlying data in an Excel spreadsheet were to change, so would the visualization.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Power BI provides the tools for a user to create different types of visualizations to communicate the data that they are using.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Some examples of these visualizations include graphs, maps, and clustered columns.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Power BI pulls data from Excel that can be used to create dashboards and visualizations.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Whereas Excel does not import data from Power BI.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Excel is typically used for less data and Power BI is more complex.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Power BI can be used to display trends over time.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, a company can create a time plot that shows its costs and revenues over a certain period.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The data can then be arranged to show per day, month, quarter, year, etc.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] This requires simple formatting tools so the data can quickly be changed and compared.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Power BI allows the user to customize their visualizations by adding colors and labels.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In addition, when the user clicks a data point, they are able to understand what the point or selection is showing.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Power BI also has a commonly used map feature where businesses can view their sales and earnings across different states and countries.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Places with the highest amounts of data will appear larger in size.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, a state with the most revenue will be bigger than states with less data.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Power BI is also interactive in that in any type of map a person can expand a specific category to look deeper into the data contained.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Tableau is another program that allows users to create dashboards.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Allegedly, One of Tableau's biggest advantages is how much data it can hold.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Tableau can hold an unlimited amount, whereas an Excel spreadsheet has a capacity of 1,048,576 rows.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] However, it is possible to hold and analyze effectively billions of rows in Excel, using its Power Pivot feature.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Tableau has the ability to make interactive dashboards by clicking into a specific point.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, you can have data be displayed within a map.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] By clicking a specific state or city you can get a closer look at the data contained within that location.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Filters and parameters can also be added.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] For example, if one were to analyze revenues across the United States you could set a parameter to only show salaries within a particular range.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Once set, only states within this range will be highlighted.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Excel has many tools that help the user not only implement data but also visualize data.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Excel has many built in functions that can help break down data and also separate data by scenarios.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The user can easily download and add files to their Excel sheets to use for their data.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Other tools Excel offers is the use of conditional formatting and basic pivot tables and charts.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Excel allows the user to reference other cells which ultimately allows for complex computations to be made and conclusions to be drawn from data.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] There are certain guidelines that can be useful when creating dashboards and other visualizations.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The guidelines have a structure that can be followed and that is beginning with reading direction.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] When it comes to how you are arranging your information on your dashboard or a visualization it can be helpful to think about reading direction.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] General reading direction is from left to right and from top to bottom.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Having information flow in this structure will allow others to read and understand your visuals in a more natural structure.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Local proximity is another idea to keep in mind when creating a visual or a dashboard.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Having information in a close proximity can be compared with a better effectiveness and allow users to draw conclusions.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Being able to make sure the user is not being overloaded with information when creating your visual.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Having a few key figures with significant importance can be more helpful compared to having too much information.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] When you have too much information and not a structure to what you are presenting then that is known as a “data graveyard”.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Another aspect to keep in mind while creating visuals that goes along with information overload is the idea of interaction within your visual.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Interacting with the dashboard would allow for further detail to be obtained from the user and allow them to better understand the information on your dashboard.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Chart visualization is an important aspect when creating dashboards, diagrams in particular.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] When you have complex data it can be difficult to come to conclusions from that material and being able to have different visual elements within the dashboard can be helpful in giving a larger overview of the material.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Being able to have a visual reporting system allows multiple processing operations to be carried out and that could increase the effectiveness of decisions.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] There are different types of visualizations that can be seen as more effective depending on the data type and the recipient.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Looking at traditional business graphics in an interactive form is another aspect to keep in mind when creating a dashboard.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Business charts are used mainly in the form of interactive dashboards.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] A major advantage of business charts is that the majority of users have an understanding of them.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] There are many connections between dashboards and accounting.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards aid with budgeting, management control, and wage control.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards are used to present data in a quick and easy to read way.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The ability to present data in a quick way with a visual allows for more data to be processed and understood.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards are used for performance reports, sales analysis on sectors, and inventory rotation.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards should be quick visualizations that allow decisions to be made quicker than they usually would without the access to dashboard technology.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] Dashboards are also used in accounting decision making settings.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] The data can help prove a change is efficient or inefficient and therefore help with improving systems throughout an organization.
[src:bullet-graphs/dashboard-business] In order for a dashboard to be efficient, the individual creating the dashboard needs to make sure that the information is simple and easy to read and be interpreted.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Markings and visual elements can be called chartjunk if they are not part of the minimum set of visuals necessary to communicate the information understandably.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Another kind of chartjunk skews the depiction and makes it difficult to understand the real data being displayed.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Examples of this type include items depicted out of scale to one another, noisy backgrounds making comparison between elements difficult in a chart or graph, and 3-D simulations in line and bar charts.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] The term *chartjunk* was coined by Edward Tufte in his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* based on ideas and materials developed for a Princeton statistics course co-taught with John Tukey.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] The term has been associated with Tufte in other references.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] In *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information* Tufte claims that good design is founded in minimalist design principles.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Specifically, he states that "graphics reveal data" if they are designed with "graphical integrity." Tufte, through minimalist design principles, was committed to an objective and neutral values of science.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Other researchers have argued that minimalism is not objective and is full of its own rhetoric and potential to bias.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Tufte, in coining the term chartjunk, also made direct comments about a well-known designer at that time, Nigel Holmes.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] This debate between Tufte and Holmes is emblematic of the tension between statistical and designerly approaches to visualization design.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] The term chartjunk is an umbrella term that can be used to describe a variety of visual devices and has been referenced by different terms across research.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Alternative terms include *embellishment,* *excessive annotation*, decoration, *extraneous elements*, and *unnecessary ornamentation*.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] Robert Kosara, also a data visualization practitioner, researcher, and author of the blog EagerEyes, noted that not all chartjunk are the same, some are harmful (e.g. a busy background), others harmless (e.g. nice borders or pictures), and some even helpful (e.g. annotations).
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] In a recent study by Parsons and Shukla, they interviewed data visualization designers and found that there is both a "corrective movement" in the design community to move away from minimalist design principles, but also, that designers had different definitions for what constitutes chartjunk.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] The information visualization research community has researched the effects of chartjunk on how viewers interpret visualizations.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] There have been studies that found that chartjunk increases long-term memorability of the chart.
[src:bullet-graphs/data-ink-ratio] A recent study found that chartjunk, in the form of semantically meaningful icons, increased accessibility of charts for people with Intellectual and Developmental Disabilities (IDD).
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] A **sparkline** is a very small line chart, typically drawn without axes or coordinates.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] It presents the general shape of a variation (typically over time) in some measurement, such as temperature or stock market price, in a simple and highly condensed way.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] Whereas a typical chart is designed to professionally show as much data as possible, and is set off from the flow of text, sparklines are intended to be succinct, memorable, and located where they are discussed.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] Sparklines are small enough to be embedded in text, or several sparklines may be grouped together as elements of a small multiple.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] In 1762 Laurence Sterne used typographical devices in his sixth volume of The Life and Opinions of Tristram Shandy, Gentleman to illustrate his narrative proceeding: "These were the four lines I moved through my first, second, third, and fourth volumes,–".
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] The 1888 monograph describing the 1883 eruption of Krakatoa shows barometric signatures of the event obtained at various stations around the world in the same fashion, but in separate plates (VII & VIII), not within the text.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] Edward Tufte documented a compact style in 1983 called "intense continuous time-series".
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] He introduced the term *sparkline* in 2006 for "small, high resolution graphics embedded in a context of words, numbers, images", which are "data-intense, design-simple, word-sized graphics".
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] Later in 2020, Tufte attributed the idea to Donald Knuth's "METAFONTbook".
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] The first software sparkline was programmed in 1999 by Peter Zelchenko.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] He introduced "an inline-chart" feature for Mike Medved's QuoteTracker.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] TD Ameritrade later discontinued QuoteTracker.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] On May 7, 2008, Microsoft employees filed a patent application for the implementation of sparklines in Microsoft Excel 2010.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] The application was published on November 12, 2009, prompting Tufte to express concerns about patent breadth and non-novelty.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] On 23 January, 2009, MultiRacio Ltd. published an OpenOffice.org Calc extension named "EuroOffice Sparkline".
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] On March 3, 2022, Tomaž Vajngerl implemented sparklines in LibreOffice Calc version 7.4, including support for importing sparklines from the OOXML Workbook format.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] Sparklines are frequently used in line with text.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] The sparkline should be about the same height as the text around it.
[src:bullet-graphs/sparkline] Tufte offers some useful design principles for the sizing of sparklines to maximize their readability.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:bullet-graphs/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
